l or not equals to the default host), display note on abstarct page -->", "    ", "    <h1 class=\"articleTitle\">Making Claims: Knowledge Design, Capture, and Sharing in HCI</h1>", "    <h2 class=\"journalTitle\"><a href=\"/toc/hci/5/3\">Synthesis Lectures on Human-Centered Informatics</a></h2>", "    <div>June 2012,", "            125 pages, (<a href=\"https://doi.org/10.2200/S00423ED1V01Y201205HCI015\">https://doi.org/10.2200/S00423ED1V01Y201205HCI015</a>)</div>", "        ", "        <!-- Start full text content -->", "        ", "        <!-- abstract content --><div class=\"Authors\"><span class=\"name noWrap\">D. Scott<span class=\"NLM_x\"> </span>McCrickard</span><span class=\"wbr\">&#8203;&#8204;</span><div class=\"aff\"> <span class=\"institution\"> Virginia Tech </span> </div></div><div class=\"hlFld-Abstract\"> <p class=\"summary-title\"><b>Abstract</b></p> <p>Human-centered informatics (HCI) is a young discipline that is still  defining its core components, with approaches rooted in engineering,  science, and creative design. In the spirit of this book series, this book  explores HCI as an intersection point for different perspectives of  computing and information technology, seeking to understand how groups of  designers can communicate with an increasingly diverse set of colleagues on  a broadening set of problems. In so doing, this book traces the evolution of  claims as a way to capture and share knowledge, particularly in comparison  to other approaches like patterns and issues. Claims can be a centrally  important aspect in HCI design efforts, either consciously by targeted  design techniques or through ingrained habits of experienced designers. An  examination of claims, their uses in design, and the possibilities for  explicit use in future collaborative design endeavors seeks to inspire their  further development use in HCI design. </p> <p class=\"last\"> Table of Contents: What are Claims? / Knowing and Sharing / Evolution of Claims / Using Claims / Looking Forward </p> </div><!-- /abstract content --><!-- fulltext content --><!-- /fulltext content -->", "        <div class=\"article_link\">", "        <table align=\"center\" cellspacing=\"10\">", "        <tr>", "    ", "    ", "    ", "    ", "        ", "            <td align=\"center\" nowrap=\"nowrap\">", "                <a href=\"/doi/pdf/10.2200/S00423ED1V01Y201205HCI015\" class=\"header4\" target=\"_blank\">", "                    PDF", "                    <span class=\"fileSize\">", "                        ", "                        (3897 KB)", "                    </span>", "                </a>", "            </td>", "            ", "    ", "            ", "            <td align=\"center\" nowrap=\"nowrap\">", "                <a href=\"/doi/pdfplus/10.2200/S00423ED1V01Y201205HCI015\" class=\"header4\" target=\"_blank\">", "                    PDF Plus", "                    <span class=\"fileSize\">", "                        ", "                        (3344 KB)", "                    </span>", "                </a>", "            </td>", "            ", "       ", "        ", "        ", "    ", "    ", "    ", "</tr>", "        </table>", "        </div>", "        ", "        ", "        <div class=\"citedBySection\" id=\"citart1\"><a name=\"citedBySection\"></a><h2>Cited by</h2><div class=\"citedByEntry\"><span class=\"name noWrap\">Joon Suk<span class=\"NLM_x\"> </span>Lee</span><span class=\"NLM_x\"><x>, </x></span><span class=\"name noWrap\">Margaret<span class=\"NLM_x\"> </span>Dickey-Kurdziolek</span><span class=\"NLM_x\"><x>, </x></span><span class=\"name noWrap\">Stacy<span class=\"NLM_x\"> </span>Branham</span><span class=\"wbr\">&#8203;&#8204;</span>. 2018. A Design Provocation for Humble Designers and Empowered Users. Design, User Experience, and Usability: Designing Interactions, 51-61. <br /><span class=\"CbLinks\"><!--noindex--><a class=\"ref\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-91803-7_4\" target=\"_blank\" title=